-- China Adds Most Crude Reserves Amid Global Increase, OPEC Says
-- B y   R u p e r t   R o w l i n g
-- 2013-07-29T13:05:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-29/china-adds-most-crude-reserves-amid-global-increase-opec-says.html
China ’s crude oil reserves rose by
the most in 2012, making it the 11th largest holder of oil
globally, according to OPEC. Worldwide inventories increased by
0.9 percent.  Proven reserves in China gained by 26 percent to 25.6
billion barrels, overtaking Qatar, the  Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries  said today in its Annual Statistical
Bulletin. The volume of available oil in  Colombia  grew by 16
percent and 12 percent in Argentina.  Venezuela and Saudi Arabia, the two largest holders of oil
globally, notched up increases to 298 billion barrels and 266
billion respectively for 2012, according to OPEC. Global
reserves increased to 1.48 trillion, the group said.  The figures for the U.S. and Canada were unchanged from
2011 at 23.3 billion and 4.9 billion respectively as the data
only include conventional crude.  According to the producer group, OPEC holds 81 percent of
the world’s oil, or 1.2 trillion barrels. Its members are
Algeria, Angola, Ecuador, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria,
Qatar,  Saudi Arabia , the United Arab Emirates and Venezuela.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Rupert Rowling in London at 
